</script>

You can't see it, but your brain reads it. Alignment is the secret grid that makes a layout feel intentional or like it was built on a trampoline.

There are two main approaches:

**Edge alignment** — All left edges (or right, or top) line up in a straight line. It feels organized and scannable.

**Center alignment** — Everything's centered on one axis. Great for special moments. Not great for whole interfaces.

Most layouts use edge alignment. Center alignment is the party trick you use sparingly.

## The Line Count Test

Imagine vertical lines through your layout. How many do you need to cover all the text and elements? Two or three? Good. More than five? You've got a problem. Fewer unique lines mean more harmony.

## Before: Scattered

