      <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 ml-2">tasks completed</p>
    </div>
    <p class="text-sm text-blue-600 text-right cursor-pointer">See full report →</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 text-center">Three different alignments. Nothing shares a line.</p>
  </div>
</Preview>

## After: One To Rule 'Em All

<Preview>
  <div class="p-6 bg-white font-sans max-w-sm border border-gray-100 rounded-xl shadow-sm space-y-4">
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Your Dashboard</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-1">Here's what happened today</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">42</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-0.5">tasks completed</p>
    </div>
    <button class="text-sm text-blue-600 font-medium hover:text-blue-700 transition-colors">
      See full report →
    </button>
  </div>
</Preview>

Everything shares the same left edge. Your eye glides down without zigzagging.

## Quick Audit

Open your design tool and draw vertical lines. If you have more than 2–3 unique left edges, you've got misaligned elements. Move them back in line.

For content areas, use a container with consistent padding so the left edge comes for free.

## Quick Recap (No Funny Title For This One)

- Left alignment is the default. Center alignment is for special cases.
- Fewer invisible lines mean more harmony.
- Use containers and padding to keep everything aligned.
- Test by drawing vertical lines through your layout.
